The Budapest!  Black is looking for a knife-fight.

Black's other option is horrible: 3...Ne4 (known as the Fajarowicz Variation) 4.a3! b6 (probably best: 4...Qh4?! 5.g3 Qh5 6.Bg2 Qxe5 7.Nf3 gives white a decisive lead in development; 4...Nc6 is considered the main line but after 5.Nf3 d6 6.Qc2!  and black soon finds himself in trouble for example 6...d5 7.e3 Bg4 8.cxd5 Qxd5 9.Bc4 (the point behind Qc2) Qa5+ 10.Nbd2 black's got nothing) 5.Nf3 Bb7 6.Nbd2 a5 7.Nxe4 Bxe4 8.Bf4 Na6 9.g3 Nc5 10.Bg2 followed by 11.Rc1 and 12.O-O black has no compensation for the pawn and a worse position as well.

The immediate 4...Bb4+ has no bite after 5.Nc3 Qe7 6.Bd2! Nxe5 8.Nxe5 Qxe5 9.a3 Bxc3 (not 9...Bc5 10.Nd5 followed by 11.Bc3) 10.Bxc3 Qg5 11.h4! Qh6 12.Rh3! and black's K is in some trouble. In particular 12...O-O is answered with 13.Rg3.

7.a3 is also playable but seems to give black some play after 7...Ngxe5 8.Nxe5 (not 8.axb4?? Nd3 mate!) 8...Nxe5 9.e3 Bxd2+ 10.Qxd2 d6 11.Be2 b6! and the black bishop will become an annoyance along the a8-h1 diagonal which supports counter-play on the K-side
Black has some problems to solve here the primary one being what to do with the dark-square bishop.

?! Black does not have enough development for this. Black's best try here is probably 9...a5! looking to restrain white on the Q-side with 10...Bxd2 and 11...a4 (white is threatening to gain space with a3 & b4).
And so ends black's "initiative."
Gaining the bishop pair.
Black has nothing and is about to develop king safety issues
!? trying to keep the black king in the center.
The immediate 14...O-O-O 15 cxd6 is troublesome for black for example 15...Rxd6 16.Qa5! or 15...cxd6 16.f3 Bd7 17.Rc1+ or 15...Qxd6 16.Qxd6 cxd6 17.f3 Bd7 18.Rc1+
Losing the g-pawn but otherwise black's king will be stuck in the center with no prospects.
! Now white returns the pawn to activate his rooks.
Prevents the N from coming back to defend the black K
! First things first - white needs to secure his own king
23...Rxd8 loses the h-pawn.
Attacking both the b & e pawns
? Black puts up more resistance with 25...Kc8 though after 26.Qxe5 white's connected central passed pawns will be enough to secure the win.
Black is lost.
26...Qxh4 27.Qa8+ and 28.Qxh8 is an easily won Q+P endgame. Black's scattered pawns will be impossible to defend.
Black is out of checks
28...Qf7 29.Qb8+ and 30.Rxc7+ or 28...Rf7 29.Qb8+ Ke7 30.Rxc7+ Kf6 (30...Ke6 31.Qfe8+) 31.Qh8+ Kg6 31.Qg8+ also lose material. 28...Ke8 29.Qxc7 is similar to the game continuation
Threatening Rc8 mate.
Black resigns as the Q is lost.

Queen's pawn. One of my favorite openings. It usually leads to expansive and open games (which I tend to loose but still enjoy)
Nothing strange he replies in kind.
Queen's gambit. I love this opening for if he accepts the gambit by playing dxe4 I'll reply with e5 immediately opting for control of the center squares and attacking his c-file isolated pawn.

Then he plays a strange move. Mistake by my calculation. This move is also not in the GK database. This move protects the d-pawn but it impairs development. The e-file pawn cannot advance and the dark square bishop (DSB) is blocked in.

e6 would be better do decline the gambit.
Developing the queen's side pieces re-enforcing my control of the center while attacking d5.

Protecting the d-pawn.

Another mistake as this reduces developing options for the knight on b8.
Developing.
Black plays an unusual response to my first move presumably trying to get away from the "book" lines.
Now I have a chance to cement an early material advantage without falling behind in development.
The preliminaries are over...
...and the game proper begins. With both center Pawns out of the way I can develop quickly.
Aiming at Q5. As long as I can prevent ...P-Q4 my KP will give me a space advantage in the center.
Adding support to the KP.
Developing with a pin.
Preparing to castle...
...and I do.
Looking to centralize the Knight...
..but first I have to deal with Black's Pawn thrust....
...and now I want to exchange and get *Black's* knight out of the center.
Down 2 Pawns Black obligingly exchanges for me bringing my Queen out without loss of time.
Pinning the B and virtually forcing Black to castle.
With Black's K where it is if I can just get rid of his Knight I could play QxP mate. H'mmm...
Black doesn't see my threat. He thinks I merely moved the Q to get it out from the Bishop's fire.
Now mate or serious material loss is inevitable. 16... P-KR3! drives the QB and kills the mate threat.

Black can play 17... P-R3 [or 17... P-N3] stopping the mate but after 18 BxB forking Q and R he would be hopelessly behind in material. 17... PxB still falls to 18 QxP mate. 17... R-K1 merely delays it by a move [18 QxP ch K-B1 19 Q-R8 mate.]
Not seeing the threat he completes the exchange of minor pieces.
The curtain falls.
Πρωτοτυπία των Λευκών. Αντι για την συνηθισμένη βαριάντα στην άμυνα 2Ι...
Ίσως καλύτερα 6... Αβ4+ και στο 7.γ3 Αε7

Φαίνεται ελκυστικό και το  7. Qf3 hxg5 8. Bxd5 
Αλλά μετά απο το 8...Qf6! 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 η θέσι φαίνεται περίπλοκη.

Δεν είναι καλό.
Καλύτερα  8... Αε7 ή 
8... Αδ6

Προτιμότερη φυσικά η βαριάντα:
9... Ke7 10. Ng5 Nf6! 11. Nxe6 Nxh5 12. Nxd8 Kxd8 13. Nc3 Nd4 14. Bb3 Bd6 
με περιπλοκές και ανοικτό παιχνίδι!

?
Καλύτερα: 10... η6
Δεν καταφέρνει και πάρα πολλά η συνέχεια: 10... Be7 11. Nbc3 O-O 
12. Nxd5! Bxd5 13. Qg6 Bxc4 14. Bxh6 +/-

Αντι για 11.Βχε5 ενδιαφέρον παρουσιάζει το Σάχ με τον Α: 
11. Bb5+ c6 12. Qxe5 cxb5 13. Nd6+ +-
Και εδώ πάλι ενδιαφέρον φαίνεται το 12.Αβ5+

Δεν είναι κακό αλλά καλύτερο είναι το : 14. Qf3+ 
Π.χ. Kg7 15. Qf6+ Kg8 16. Qe6+ Kg7 
(όχι βέβαια 16... Kh7 διότι υπάρχει Μάτ σε 2)
17. Bd2 Ned5 18. c4 +-

Δεν λυτρώνει τον Μαύρο ούτε το: 14... Bg7 
Π.χ. 15. Qf4+ Kg8 16. Nf6+ Bxf6 17. Qxf6 +-
15.Βχθ8 ! (Κι ας υπάρχει και το 15.Βζ4+ !)
Φαίνεται πως τα Μαύρα εγκλώβισαν την Λευκή Β...

16.Ιη5!
Η τύχη είναι με το μέρος των ισχυρών!

Κι όμως! Ο Μαύρος αντι 16… Ρζ6? έπρεπε να πάρη τον Ίππο στο η5 
με ακόμα αρκετό παιχνίδι π.χ.: 16... hxg5 17. Qh3 Rh8 18. Qg3 Be5 
19. f4 Bd4+ 20. Kh1 Nf5 21. Qxg5 και τώρα 
21... Qd8! 22. Qg4!  (22. Qxd8?? Ng3! #) 
Αλλά έτσι φτάνουμε σε μια θέσι που κόβη την ανάσα και στους 2 αντιπάλους.

Με ολύμπια ψυχραιμία αλλά και το εναλλακτικό: 17. Qh7 
είναι εξ ίσου αποτελεσματικό: π.χ.: 
17...hxg5 18. Nc3 Qe5 19. Ne4+ +-

Αλλιώς: 
17... ΠχΒθ8 18.Ιχδ5+ Ιβχδ5 20.Ιε4+ +/- +-
ή 18.Ιηε4+ Ρζ7 19.Ιχδ5 με (σχεδόν) κερδισμένη θέσι για τα Μαύρα.

Εδώ ο Λευκός είναι μάλλον λάθος.
Απλώς έπρεπε να πάρη τον Αη7!
: 18. Qxg7+! Kxg7 19. Ne6+ +-

18…ΒχΑε3?
Θα ήταν μικρότερο το κακό για τον Μαύρο αν έπαιρνε την Βασίλισσα με τον Α. 
π.χ.: 18... Bxh8 19. Bxd4+ Kxg5 20. Be3+ (20. Bxh8 Rxh8 21. Rae1 Nc6)
και στις δύο περιτώσεις όμως τα Λευκά κερδίζουν.

19... ΡχΙη5 +-
Μόνο φαινομενικά καλύτερο το Ιζ5 π.χ. : 19... Nf5 
20. Nce4+ Ke7 21.Qxg7+! +- 
ή ακόμα και 21.Rxf5!? Bxh8 22. Rf7+ Ke8 23. Rh7 Bxb2 
24. Ne6 Bxa1 25. c3 Nd5 26. c4 Nxe3 27. Nxc7+ Kf8 28. Nxa8 +-

Πλάκα έχει και η ψευδοθυσία: 21. Rf4! 
π.χ. 21... Bxh8 22. Ng3+ Kg5 23. h4#

μπορούσαν να κάνουν Μάτ σε 2 κινήσεις και μάλιστα με 2 διαφορετικούς τρόπους.

My third loss out of three "walking the walk" club games.  My assessment is that bad moves at 12 16 and 19 cost me the game.  Sixteen I can live with though hopefully will not repeat.  But 12 and 19 were careless.  Hopefully I will learn from these mistakes and use these lessons to strengthen my game.
Reti opening transposes in to English.
I am reasonably happy with the opening so far.

...but because of what comes after this move turns out to be problematic.  I did want to free up my queen's rook.  But I should not have put the bishop on f4 the problem being that once black's knight goes to c6 I have poor options for protecting my d-pawn and e5 can become a forking square for black.  Or perhaps I'm overthinking things and pxp would have been good enough.
I still have not recognized the problem I mentioned earlier.
and I still think I am in good shape here.  But despite considering my next move for some time...

...I make this poor move.  Game losing mistake.  I had considered moving the bishop back but stubbornly thought of how that would represent a wasted move (given that I could have gone to d2 or e3 at move 10).  It did not occur to me that black would play g5 here.

But of course he did.  Certainly a loss of more than 1 point value for black to let go of that particular pawn.  Regardless I am very annoyed with myself having just played poorly during the opening in my previous wtw game vs ionadowman.
Of quite a few options this seemed ok ...no worse than an immediate capture of the attacking pawn. And it gave me a bit more time to search for a solution.

now to see if I can quickly take advantage of black's king's reduced protection.  Dark square bishop will likely be captured next move.  I'm looking at g1 and g3 as potentially good places to put my rooks (though the rook on the d-file is happy enough for now).  For the moment despite being down in material I believe I have a slight mobility advantage.  To free up his N & lsb I expect black's rook will move to c8 (or poss Q to c7 or d7).  So any mobility advantage will vanish very soon.

I considered capture with g-pawn here.  but 16. ...Re8 would have given black a good escape route.  What I fail to appreciate is that capturing with the e-pawn removes important protection from d4 which black's N will come to comfortably occupy.  Too much ambition and not enough caution.

Will white be able to make good use of the open e-file?  Or will there be a trade-off where black comes out ahead?  Can I put a rook on g before black can defend?  In retrospect I should have captured with the g-pawn primarily to keep protection on the d4 square.  I'll count this as Major Mistake #2.

A nice move by black.  Knight threatens K-Q fork and can sit on d4 a long as it likes.  The momentary mobility advantage I thought I had was a phantom.  As mentioned I wish I still had a pawn on e3.  Plus the open file that would have come with 16. gxf4 might have been useful though it may also have been trouble.  Comments?
Protects against fork and may help with eventual rook attack on the black king.
Bishops now off the board.
limits white's pawn moves.  and I see later sets up Q to h3 ...which I could easily defend against "could" being the operative word!

Should have moved 19. Kg2!  Major Mistake #3.  Too focused on trying to rally an offense ...neglectful of limiting black's attacking options.  Whatever chance white had of exploiting black's king's "weakened" position is now gone.  White will now be on the defensive.
black takes advantage of white's poor choice.
White has to be very careful as black now has a number tactical possibities.
Puts 2x protection on e2.
White intends to reduce black's many tactical possibilities by pushing his queen back.
most moves here lose for white.  a tempting move Rxg4 really only leads to a trade-off of rooks or worse.  attacking the queen loses the attacking rook (by 23. ...Ne2+).
allows R to go to g3.  still black's 4 pieces to my 3 doesn't look good.  too bad b4 won't do a thing to knock that horse off his comfortable outpost.
RxR = QxR#.  Threatening Q = QxR+.  Capturing pawn w/check leads to loss of rook.  PxP = QxQ.  stalhandske's screen name suits him well.
ok for a second.  but once black releases pin white's f-pawn will be attacked 3 times.
all roads lead to disaster.  black's pieces are extremely well arrayed either defending or attacking.  Per the club "Rules" (play the game out) I'll see if I can do something to improve my situation.
that pawn was almost as menacing as black's 4 pieces.  it figured in to several mating or capturing scenarios.  still 4 to 3 though.
no way out.  white will have no defense for 27. ...R8e2.  resigns.  Thank you to stalhandske for the game.  commenters will please advise if there was a way out after 19. f3.

The game was quite an interesting positional struggle. with an odd sort of prison occuring around my king. My opponent for this game is meant to be a very expierenced dangerous player however he does have a tendancy to play slightly to fast and is notourios for making these horrific blunders one such won me this game however there was some intersting play before that.

The symmetrical english I have played this a couple of times now from blacks perspective and am starting to really enjoy it. During this game black (myself) played something of a very hypermodern style by allowing my opponent to overextend and then take advantage of the weaknesses later.
Normally I would just play Bg7 however this time I played this instead.
preparing the thematic d pawn push. Here I decided on a whim to try something a little different from the norm.

!? This came from some of my limited expierence from playing white in the english system. I often found a few times that by waiting too long for the d pawn push I began having problems when black took advantage of the hole created on d3. This move although it violates the principle that one should avoid moving a piece more than once in the opening does force whites hand. I think the loss of tempi is justified as it forces white to play in a way he is unfammilier with.
Practically forced.

?! very agressive. I suspect my oponent is underestimating me in this game. I'm young and my only expierence playing this opponent tendid to be when I was still very new to chess. Now I'm starting to develop something of an appreciation for positonal play so although far from being good I'm slowly learning how to take advantage of some weaker moves my opponents occasionally play. As white I think I would be considering instead moves like Ne2 Nf3 or maybe even b3. This move however is not that bad when it comes down to it.
The only other square being g4 and I didn't like the idea of playing my knights over to the king side. black needs to remain flexible in this position.

I decided to play a restrained sort of game once again as well this comes from expierence playing the english I often had troubles when my opponents opposed my King side fianchettoe as well as that I noticed that black doesn't do too badly in some of the games I have seen in the symmetrical english.
I think it's usually best to complete a fianchetto as soon as possible when you start one.

The only reason white would play this move is he intends to play the f pawn foward. It's not a plan I would have chosen as white but I supose everyone has there own styles besides it's consistent with whites play so far what with the f pawn thrust before. Other moves that may have been sensible were e4 since the d pawn cant make its advance and must become backward then perhaps the e pawn will be the one to make its way foward. b3 planning to use the LSB on the a1-h8 diagonal and Re1 both seem to be potential ideas

?! intended to give support to my b7 bishop and allow my knight to move should it be worthwhile probably this was a waste of time. Had I given some thought to the reason behind my opponents previous move I may have have made the more logical move e6 which prevents any advance my my opponents f pawn as well as preparing a potential d pawn thrust. It would also make my opponents previous move look silly.
well with Nh4 not much else would make any sense.
Hoping to get rid of whites LSB. Perhaps 0-0 or e6 should have been played instead.

This was probably going to occur at some stage anyway however now boths sides plans are becoming slightly more clear. Black intends to make use of the a1-h8 diagonal and maybe plant knights on d4 and e5 via d6-Nd7-Nde5 and the knight curently on e5 will go back to c6 to aim for d4. white it seems plans to press blacks position and see if he can drum up some form of attack. White should be able to make good use of the nice diagonal c1-h6 and maybe even look to trade DSB.
This or else d6. possibly even Nc6. I think the move I made was correct.
Since I cant move the knight this seems alright. If I was to play d6 then Bxe5!? would be worth looking at for white the point being that Bxe5 dxe5 seems to be bad for black.

So I made this move almost instantly. White cant trade the bishop for the knight. I never considered trying to get a knight to e3. What does the reader think? would Ng4 (either knihgt) have been worth looking into?
playing to plant a knight on d4.
?! Very provocative and probably a little weakning.
The b8-h2 diagonal is significanly stronger playing this plays on that diagonal. Possibly  should have played a6 first to prevent Nb5
Good move by white it threatens to exchange DSB which black cant afford. I mentioned before that this was a good diagonal for white and this emphasise that fact.
in order to keep control over the long diagonal. Now if white plays Bh6 I can just drop my bishop back to h8.
Black was going to play d6 anyway so perhaps this move was unwise. Instead Bh6 or maybe exchanging pawns could have been played for this and the last few moves.

This move baffles me a bit. What was whites plan? Instead of this Bh6 Nf3 to give some extra control over e5 or possibly even exchanging with fxg would be better they would actually be part of a plan at any rate.
Puts two more pieces on e5. It also prepares to land the knight there.

I didn't quite know what to think at this point. white has a lot of pieces around my king does he have an attack? I dont know. I chose to continue with my own plans by making use of all these squares I have worked so hard to create.

At this point I realised that the whites king side advance had effectvly been halted. With the kingside practially shut down its time for black to swicth and start pushing himself but on the queen side where black seems to have better prospects.
?! I'm not quite sure what this move accomplishes. white should probably make something happen on the kingside.
Black was eventually going to move here anyway but now it also threatns a fork.
I was slightly unsure how to proceed here I thought by doing this I might be able to somehow find a better use for my LSB than what its doing right now.
A good square for the white knight.

I decided upon this square by rationalisng that this was the most promosing diagonal for the queen. Also it prepares to push e6. My LSB isn't going to be of much use this game so possibly I should have exchanged it for the knight.
interesting choice of recapture by white. Which one was best here? I'm not too sure.

I had a good long think at this point in the game. I was trying to decide between exf6 or this move. I thought exf plans to make a target of whites f pawn however it frees his DSB yet leaves mine still very uninfluential. Thus I decided on this move. Now both players are effectivly playing without dark square bishops. For that matter as well my king could probably have no better protection from any middle game attacks. Though this move has plenty of down sides as well which I will outline later.
I assume white was using his king to protect the h3 pawn. However this square is really a very poor square for the white king.

targeting the weak d pawn. Blacks position seems quite nice at the moment certaitnly it's easy to play since it has clear plans as well as that black has those great knights in the centre strong quuenside pawns and whites pieces seem uncordinated and kind of not doing much on the kingside.
Incase the a file ever were to open. it also clears the b8 square for my other rook and allows Ra7 where I can choose to double rooks if I ever choose to.
I probably played this to give my queen a6.

What was this move all about? perhaps the reader has ideas about why white may be doing this does it somehow prepare to start moving the kingside pieces over to the queen side? in my opinion white needs to move the king in order to do that. Blacks knights are doing a really good job of keeping whites position under raps.
getting my rook out of line from the LSB as well as allowing a double up at some point.

?? It's almost a shame for white to end the game so suddenly with this blunder. When there was so much play still left in it. How does the reader evaluate the position had white not blundered? To me it is very interesting. It seems on the surface that black is much better. He has these strong knights much easier play especially on the queenside where he can slowly advance the pawns and white right now is full of weaknesses and whites pieces are uncordinated inactive and will take a very long time to be made use of. However it seems to me that white has some good long term prospects with some accurate play. the key being that if white can get to an endgame he will be practially won. With blacks king completely out of play black would be effectivly a piece down since come endgame the kings become very useful attacking pieces as well as that black will have a permanant back rank weakness. However it is difficult to achieve this and would require some very precise moves from white to make use of these features.
Well this was an interesting game and a good result for me I'm interested to see how the reader evaluates some of the positions in this games especially near the end.

He offers a draw and I accept since I don't have enough for another attack. Thank  you for reading! Please rate and comment! Thank you once again alfil for this great game!
The King's Pawn Play.
I decide to play the double kings knight opening instead of the Sicilian Defense.
This is where he decides to develop his minor pieces but I cannot figure out why he did this on the queen's side instead of the king's side.
At this point I threaten to force an exchange with Bxc3 and dxc3.
He attempts to prevent the exchange by playing a3 because he does not want two bad pawns since two pawns would be on the c file but he is not successful because the exchange is inevitable.
Now I bring out my knight in the attempt to capture his free pawn but he does not allow this to happen.

This was not a great move because he could have played e5 and threatened me with exf6 and that would have been his best move.  However he did not think about the feasibility because he was worried about his pawn on e4 since I was threatening to play Nxe4.  Therefore he played f3 to prevent this from happening.
Now I try to force an exchange with d5 but am unsuccessful.
He responds with c4 in order to get rid of his bad pawns and it works because he forces an exchange with dxc4 and Bxc4.
Now I decide to check him in order to force an exchange with Qxd1+ and Kxd1.
By playing e5 I prevent him from threatening me with exf6.

Instead I force an exchange with Rxc7 and Rxc7 and it is great because I exchange my pawn for his rook.

After he moves his king I force another great exchange.  That is because I capture more pieces then him because I capture with two of my pieces but he only captures with only one piece.  This exchange occurs when Rhxh7 Rxh7 and Kxh7 are played.

In this particular game I made many mistakes during the beginning and middle games but I did not give up because I remembered Jack Stockel's advice to "Think about things".  I also remembered from Jack Stockel that there are usually second chances to correct mistakes after a mistake has been made.  As a result I was able to trick my opponent into a three fold repetition.  That trick is shown here from moves 12-16.
I made this move to prevent my opponent from playing d5 and threatening my knight with exc3.

This move was made to threaten my opponents knight on the f square with Bxf6.  If I was able to capture his knight I would have been able to mess up his pawns.  In other words I would have been able to put him in a situation so that two of his pawns would be on the same square.

This was a big mistake because I should have played Bxf6 captured his knight and forced two of his pawns on the same square.  Instead I play Qd2 to trick him and put pressure on his queen and knight.  Now he is able to eliminate this threat.
Now he plays Be7 to put pressure on my knight.  I either could have taken his knight or pulled my bishop back.  Instead I make a bigger mistake on my next move.

Now I have made one of my biggest maybe the second most serious mistake.  I played e3 without even thinking about it.  When I look at this board he could have played Ne4 with a powerful fork between my queen on the d square and my knight on the c square.  That is not the other half of the story.  He also could have left his bishop attacking bishop on the g square if he had moved his knight.  Instead he castles on his next move.
I had to pull the bishop back in order to prevent him from threatening my knight with his bishop.
This is where I decided to exchange bishops with him.  This might not have been the best move but I wanted to get his bishop off the board.
Now he likely made a mistake because he now has two bad pawns.

This was my biggest mistake.  I should have moved the knight and bishop on the other side so that I could castle on the kings side as opposed to castling on the queens side.  At this point my king is exposed.

This was another big mistake.  I should have moved my knight with Nb2 or Nb5.  Nb5 would have been my best move.  My queen would not have been allowed to break through I would have been able to win a free pawn with Nd6.

Now my knight is pinned on the c square due to my last mistake what am I going to do now?  I am not going to resign but I will try to find a way out of trouble because this where I remembered Jack Stockel's advice.  His advice was "Don't give up right away."  He would also say "If you know that you cannot win try to get a draw."

The Sicilian Defense. The only - real - option for black to gain winning chances. This opening is for experts only on both sides... White as well as black could win this...

The Grand Prix Attack cooked up by the likes of Petrosjan and Tal in blitz games. The idea is quick development via confusing the real issues: Magic... Black is already faced with 2. ... Nf6 3. e5 Nd5 4. d4.

White uses this to fight Alekhine...

The logical approach 2. ... d5 will be met by 3. e5 Nc6 4. Nf3 Bg4 5. g3 Qb6 6. Bg2 and castling options. We steal this from King's Indian... One of Fischer's favourite approaches...

The standard follow-up in most variations in the Sicilian. Right now d5 was still better... Pawn c5 needs not to be covered right now... If any covering at al... Playing black I would prefer 2. ... g6 here persuing Dragon variations or Kings Indian tendencies with Bg7/Nf6...
What white wants... After Bg4 the plan might still be g3 ... Bg2 ... 0-0
This calls for different measures... Options are 4. c3 d5 (of course) 5. e5 Bf5! with a possible bind on c2 via Nb4... The basic plan of Alekhine Defense...

We switch plans and discard the 4. g3 5. Bg2 6. 0-0 variation... White steals this from Ruy Lopez to bind Nc6 just for now... The Fischer-move Bf1-c4-b3 is too early... After 4. Bc4 e6/Nf6 clears all threats...
Now after 4. ... Nf6 5. d3 a6 6. Bxc6+ bxc6 7. e5! preventing g6 and Bg7...
Castle never too early but never too late...
After 5. ... Nf6 6. d3 a6 7. Bxc6 Bxc6 8. e5 nothing gets really solved for black... Too early for d5...

6. Nc3! stems from the Vienna variations in Queens Gambit with d4... White is gaining strong control over d5 now... The pinnacle of the Sicilian Defense: if black can play d5 and c4 it is over for white... White is soon threatening d2-d3-d4-d5... Thanks to 2. f4 Ne5/Nd4 has no meaning left...

The strongest continuation for both sides... After 6. ... Be7 also d3... For white it is too early for 7. d4... We have to give Nc6 no slack... Not good is 7. e5? dxe5 8. fxe5 (Nxe5 Nd4!) Ng4! No good for black is 7. ... d5 8. Ne5 dxe4 (on d4 also Bxc6) 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. dxe4...

For black there is more sense in 7. ... a6 persuing Najdorf tendencies... 8. Bc4 b5 9. Bb3 (the Fischer approach still controlling d5 and even f7 after f4-f5) Qb6 10. Kh1... White follows the natural lead it all evolves round e5...

This rules out d5 - for black - and we leave the Sicilian Defense strategy... A lot more problems for white poses 8. ... Ng4 attacking e5... 9. Ng5 Nh6 10. Qh5 0-0 11. exd6 Bxd6 grinds to a halt soon for white so does 10. exd6 Bxd6... After 9. h3 Nh6 10. exd6 Bxd6 11. Ne4 Be7...

Now after 9. ... Ng4 10. Qe2 keeping an eye on Ng4...
There is no glory in 10. Nxd5 exd5 (and we're back at the Sicilian) 11. Bxc6 Bxc6 12. Qe1... After 12. ... d4 13. Qg3 Bf8 14. Ng5 Bd5 or 13. ... Qd7 14. Qxg7 0-0-0 black closes his ranks...

Inaccurate attempt to an early 0-0-0. This robs black of Nc7 after c4. This gives white an extra tempo to complete his plan. After 10. ... 0-0 white has more problems. Directly 11. a4 Qc7 12. Qe1 Nd4 13. Nxd4 cxd4 14. Bxd7 Qxd7 15. c4 dxc3 16. bxc3 f5! 17. exf6 Bxf6 18. Nxf6+ Nxf6 snuffs out whites attack. After 11. c4 Nb6 12. Bf4 a6 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. Qe2 Qc7...

Fighting Alekhine springs to mind... Also 12. Bg5 0-0 13. Qd2 h6 or 13. Qe1 a6 stops white dead in his tracks... Now after 12. ... 0-0 13. a5 Nc8 14. Qe1 a6 15. Bxc6 Bxc6 16. Qg3! Bxe4 17. dxe4 Kh8 18. Bg5! black is in trouble...
12. ... a6! is sharpest for black now after missing out on move 7... Now there is no turning back for white...

Remember this knight came from g8 on move 6 fourth move now... 13. ... axb5 14. axb6 Qc8 15. Rxa8 Qxa8 16. cxb5 or 13. ... Nxa5 14. Nd6+ Bxd6 15. exd6 Qxd6 16. Bxd7+ Nxd7 17. Rxa5 b6 18. Ra3 e5 19. Be3... Longside castling is prevented for a couple of moves...

Of course we take the horse pinned at move 4; thus defending a5/e5 against Qc7... This is all part of whites plan black has much room for error now... Nc8 is a burdon and Bc6 has to be taken... But how?

After 14. ... Qxc6 15. Nfg5! Bxg5 (0-0? Qh5 h6 Rf6; f6 exf6; Rf8 Nxh7 Rh8 Qh5 threatening Nf6+) 16. Bxg5 Rf8 (Qc7? Rxf7!! Qxe5 (Kxf7?? Qh5+) Rf2) 17. Qh5 Qc7 18. Qxh7 Qxe5 19. Rae1 black is overpowered...

After 14. ... bxc6 15. Be3! threatening capture of c5 followed by b4 and d4 soon... Black is completely tied up...

 White is preparing Qg3 to start an attack against blacks kingside now; still on schedule...

After 15... O-O 16. Qg3 Bxe4 17. dxe4 Kh8 18. Ra3... Now 16. ... 0-0 17. Qg4 leads to similar variations... 16. ... Na7 (preparing 0-0-0 obvious enough) 17. Qg4 Rg8 (g6 Bg5; 0-0?? Bh6 all else fails for black) spoiling 0-0 18. Bd2 preparing attack against the queenside via c5... For now white controls most dark squares and has to keep making it black castling and untangling his position as hard as it takes...

Practically forced. White has to spend this extra tempo and threaten Bh6. We need a means to develop Bc1 with a threat and gain that extra tempo. 17. Bd2 Na7 18. Bc3 Nc6 leads to nothing 17. Be3 Na7 18. d4 cxd4 19. Nxd4 Nc6 releases all tensions 17. Bg5 Na7 goes the same way...

There is a big difference now that whites Queen is at g4 in stead of g3 in a previous meant variation. Threats against black kingside involve keeping e5 covered and lest we forget poor uncovered d3? After Nc8-a7-c6 d4 is never going to happen... Blacks best defense - therefore - lies in forcing b4/d4... 17. ... Kh8 18. Bg5 h6 (or Na7 d4) 19. Be3 Na7 or 17. ... Rd8 18. Bh6 (Ra3 Na7) Bf8 (that was blacks point) 19. Be3... Sadly 17. ... Rd8 is met with 18. Bg5! Blacks last move is loss of tempo covering Be7 is futile...

This gives white an extra tempo to compose a web of new threats. Now after playing Bg5 we also cover b2 and threaten Raf1... Be7 - just like Nc8 - becomes a liability... After 18. Bh6? Bf8 19. Bd2 Ne7! That is the whole of blacks point... After 19. Ng5 Qxe5 20. Nxf7 Qd4+ forces swapping Queens... 18. Rf2 prevents this also... Ergo: Bh6 is still a threat...

Black tries to squirm out but this is not the way. Black is hoping for Nc8-e7-g6 but he won't get on time. Correct - so to speak -  was 18. ... Na7 19. Bh6 (white has to sit this one out or else Nc6) Bf8 20. Ng5 (same) Qxe5 21. Nxf7 Qd4 (no check thanks to Rf2) 22. Qg3! (otherwise we had to swap Queens) Nc6 23. Bg5 e5... After Re1 threatening Re4 we have at least e4...

After 19. Bh6? Ne7 20. Bd2 Ng6 or better Rad8! whites attack is snuffed out... With Be7 out of the picture 19. Ng5 gains extra strength. After 19. ... Qxe5?? 20. Qh5 it's game over... All of blacks weaknesses are revealed now... Nxf7 or Qh5 is the least of blacks worries... So 19. ... g6/Re7 (Na7 Bd2 ... Raf1) is forced...

This rules out variations involving Ne7 for a little while; white must use this immediately. After 19. ... g6 20. Qh3/Qh4 h5 21. Nxf7 Re7/Bg7 22. Bh6/Ng5! white wins... After 19. ... Qxe5?? 20. Qh5 - threatening deadly Qxf7+ - black loses the Queen or mate...

This is clear enough. Only 20. ... h6 is left... After that 21. Ne4 also covering e5 completely locking up blacks position. After that we need some plan to defend d3 long enough to be able to develop Bc1...

Bxh6 is a minor threath now... Probably just strong enough to withstand Rd7 Rf3 Ne7... Given the right moment white has Nf6+ or even Rf6... For instance 21. ... g6 22. Nf6+ Kh8 (Kg7 Qxh6 mate) 23. Qh4! (threatens Bxh6) h5 24. g4... After 21. ... Kh8 22. Bxh6 gxh6 23. Rf6 without further adue... With Bc1 out of the way Raf1 is a matter of time... After 21. ... Qd8 (Rd7 Rf3) the astounding 22. Bg5 Qxd3 (hxg5? Nxg5) 23. Nxc5 g6 24. Qg4 Qd8 25. Rxf7...
Black resigned under the pressure after 21. Ne4... Here is what might have followed... After 23. ... gxh6 Rf6...

During this game I underestimated the power of my opponent's king because I allowed her to do whatever she wanted when she wanted with her king.  She only had the king and a pawn but I had the king two pawns and a knight so I was about to get a pawn promotion.  However I messed up somehow.  Therefore my opponent ended up with more pieces then I had and she also got something that I had lost a pawn promotion.  Therefore I was forced to resign from the game.
This was her "cornerstone" of the Sicilian defense.
For me it might have been better if I had played Nf3 on this move instead.  This might have then given me the opportunity to play Bc4 by move 3 and castle by move 4.
This was the move that I was referring to 2. Nc3.  Instead I did on my third move for the exact same reason with Bc4 and then castling.
Now she decides to play the Sicilian defense.  In the mean time I bring out my knights so that I am protected.

I brought out my bishop so that I could castle on my next move but I was unaware that this would be a bad time to castle.  I also realize that Bc4 was a bad move because she could have played a fork against me between my pawn on e4 and my bishop on c4.  Luckily she does not do this but instead she plays Nc6.
As I mentioned earlier this was a bad to castle.  I should have played Ng5 because she is going to bring out her bishop on her next move and threaten my knight with Bxf3.
Not only does she play Bg4 and threaten with Bxf3 but I am now pinned.  That is I cannot pull my knight away with Ng5 or I am going to loose my queen because she is going to play Bxd1.
On the other hand I play Bb5 because I am thinking "Two could play that game".  That is because I decided to pin her in return with Bb5.
I figured that I would exchange my bishop with her pawn.  That way she will have two bad pawns because two of her pawns will be on the c square but that does not happen.
Now she makes a big mistake that allows me to get a free bishop and check her.
Now she lost a pawn and is checked after I play Bxd7+ and I am just getting started.
Even though she captures my bishop with Qxd7 I still have a few surprises for her.
I try to force an exchange with her with Nxd5 and exd5 by playing Nd5 but that plan also does not work.
Instead she moves her knight away from danger with Ng4.

I do not know what I was thinking but b3 was not a great move because she threatens the knight with Qxe6 on her next move.  This move did not make a lot of sense.  I wanted to bring out my bishop and form a Fianchetto because I would not be able to capture free pieces or exchange them in this position.
I do not understand why she played Qe6 because I ask myself the following.  What piece is she threatening?  I am looking at the entire board and the queen does not seem like a threat at the moment.
At this point I decide to play a 3 way fork against her in order to capture her queen since she is checked.
This was my favorite capture of the game.
Now I decide to play a Fianchetto with Bb2.  I learned a few years ago that it is generally good if one could do this.
I am not sure why she played h5 but I believe that she did it to either capture a free a pawn or get a pass pawn.
I played Qe2 in order to prevent her from capturing a free pawn with Qxc4.
I played h3 to threaten her knight with hxg4.
I learned several years ago that one is eventually supposed to connect the rooks during the game.  That is why I played Rad1.
I forced an exchange with this move because I generally like to exchange pieces.

However this was not a good exchange because it was not even.  At the point I did not realize that I supposed to count pieces.  This is something that Jack Stockel taught me about 5 weeks ago.  Because I did not count the pieces she was able to get an extra pawn during the exchange.
In this position her rook is now threatened with Kxh3 so she is now forced to pull her rook back.
I made this move so that I could force an exchange with her with Rxh7 but this does not happen.
Instead she brings her bishop.  I believe that it is because she was trying to trick me but I was not going to be fooled.
I still force the exchange.
I played Kh2 in order to put pressure on her knight.
On the other hand she played Rh8 in to put pressure on the h square.
I played Qf2 to put pressure on her.
I decided to threaten her with gxh5 by playing g4.  As a result she was forced to pull her knight back.
I do not want know why I made this move but it was not strategically smart because it will trigger a negative chain of events.
At this points she plays a discover check against me by moving her bishop away from her rook.
This was not a good move.  I should have played Kg3 because she is going to check me in a horrible way.
Now she checks and plays a fork against so she is going to capture my queen for her knight with Nxf2.
Again she plays Rf8 in order to put pressure on the f square.
This was not a good move.  Instead I should have played Nxg5 because it would have allowed me to get a free pawn from her.
At this point she protects her pawn with her bishop.
I attempted to force an exchange by playing b4 but it did not work.
Instead she pressures the c square with her rook.
I respond with Rh1 so that I could threaten her bishop with Rxh6.
As a result she is forced to protect her bishop with Rh8.
Instead I force an exchange with her with bxc5.
This exchange works because I am able to capture an extra but this capture is a free pawn that leads to a direct check with Bxc5+.
Now that she is checked what happens after she gets out of it?  That will be answered on my next move.
I simply capture a free pawn after she recovers with Bxa7.
I do not know why she picked this candidate.
This was not a good move.
That is because she could have captured my free rook with rxh1.  It was just lucky that she did not play rxh1. Now instead she threatens me with Rxd2 by playing Rd8.
Instead I handle this situation with Rd1 but it is bad move.
That is because she threatens to capture my free bishop with Rxc5.
I stop the threat by playing Bd6 and forcing her to exchange pawns which will culminate in a serious check.
This check forced her to exchange her bishop and I got a free pawn after that.
In addition I threaten to capture another pawn with Nxg5.
At this point she plays e5 because she is forced to protect that pawn.
I decided to check her with Ne6+ but this does not do much because the check is a mere nuisance but not serious.
After she threatens to play kxe6 I respond by checking her again with my knight.  However this check is serious because I force an exchange with Rxb7 and Rxa2.
In my attempt to get a pawn promotion I play g5 as my candidate.
In her attempt to stop the pass pawn and prevent the pawn promotion she plays Ra8.
I played Rb8 in order to put pressure on the b square.
She plays Rg8 because wants to get a free pawn.
I respond and protect the pawn by playing Kg4.
She threatens to check me with Rf4+.  If she had been able to check me she would have gotten a free pawn with Rxe4.
I responded to that threat with Kh5.
Now she checks me but I do not care because this check is only a nuisance.
I do not know why she made this move for she knows that she cannot play Rxg5.
I also do not know why I chose that candidate in this position because she is not threatening to play Rxd2 at the moment.
She threatens again to check me and capture my pawn but I am oblivious to this threat.
I am trying to force an exchange but this was a bad move because I did not see the threat.  Therefore unlike last time she checks me and gets the free pawn.
Now she puts me in a serious check as part of the fork.  That's right she is playing a fork against me between my king on g4 and my pawn on e4.
After I come out of check she gets a free pawn with Rxe4.
I attempt to break through and get a pawn promotion by playing d5.
She plays Rd4 in order to prevent the break through by forcing an exchange with Rxd4 and exd4.
Now I get a pass and attempt a pawn promotion be playing g6.
She plays Kf8 in order to prevent the pawn promotion.
Since I could not get a pawn promotion with my last move I try another to get the promotion a different with d6.
While I try to get a pawn promotion she also tries for the same thing so she plays d3.
Because I played d7 I am only one step away from promoting my pawn into a queen.
She attempts to prevent the promotion by playing Ke7 and is successful

This was my biggest mistake because I underestimated the power of her king.  That is because I inferred that it did not matter what she did with her king since I was in the winning position and going to win anyway.  My best move would have been g7.  That way I would have gotten a pawn promotion and she would not be able to it from happening.  If I had played g7 and she had played Kf7 to stop the promotion I would have responded with d8=Q and the promotion would have been inevitable.  Instead I played Nc5 because I believed that this would prevent her from playing Kxg7 and inhibit her pawn promotion but I was wrong.  Jack Stockel would say "That losses immediately" with this move.

Because she played d2 and my king was not on e2 d1 d3 or c2 she was going to get a pawn promotion and I would not be able to stop it.  In addition I cannot my pawn with d8=Q because he would simply capture the promoted queen with Kxd8.
Now that she plays d2 I respond with g7 but it is officially "Too little too late" because she is now one step ahead of me so I am now doomed in this game.
This is now her inevitable pawn promotion.

I responded to her pawn promotion by promoting my pawn into a queen with g8=Q.  However it is still "Too little too late" because she is going to check me with Qg1+ and win my promoted queen with Qxg8.  In addition she will continue to check me and win other pieces such as my remaining pawn.  This forces me to resign.

This was a very good game.  In fact this was my second best loss and one of my longest games but there is and was an important lesson to learn from this game.  In the short term this game taught me not to underestimate the opponent during pawn promotions.  In the long term I learned an important fact about end games from Jack Stockel and it reminds me of this game against anitam.  It also explains how I became overconfident with anitam during the end game.  That is because he played against an opponent about two weeks ago and the opponent was winning.  In fact he almost won the game but he made some serious mistakes and lost the game because of his overconfidence.  The lesson was "When you think that you have won or you are winning be very careful and do not underestimate the opponent.  Otherwise you might start making mistakes and loosing the game."

I've played this move as prophylaxis against the thematic black's strategy on the a1-h8 diagonal so I can move my c1 bishop freely or advance my b pawn and also preparing c5-a3-b4 to avoid exchanging rooks after axb4 axb4

Until now we were following Jhunjhnuwala Ramesh (HKG) - Sammut Briffa Peter (MLT) Salonika (Greece) 1988 1-0 but I'm the first to diverge as 11.a3 played in that game is too passive I've considered two main options here 11.Rd1 to pin the d7 knight and 11.Na4 to block the a pawn and prepare c5

N improvement on the game Jhunjhnuwala Ramesh - Sammut Briffa Peter Salonika (Greece) 1988 1-0 intended to prevent the a pawn advance while avoiding Nc5 or Nb6 and even b5 as it will win a pawn cxb5 cxb5 Bxb5 a future Rd1 is also in prevision as will pin the Nd7
prevents c5
with my rook on b1 I can still prepare b4-c5 here I'm already experiencing some difficulties  as I don't have a clear plan either than to push my pawns in the queen's wing
connecting rooks and also aimed at c5
I didn't like the prospect of exchanging my bishop for the knight so I've decided to play it to g5 aimed at d8 with the idea of maybe latter play Rfd1
my Bg5 move was a bit passive so black started immediately an attack on the king side
aimed at g4 to disturb black's attack
protecting the bishop
blocks my queen
so I have no other chance than to allow the exchange of bishop for knight
but now black's structure doesn't favour his dark square bishop so in the future I'll benefit if I can exchange light squared bishops or even a knight by black's light squared bishop
if h5 then I have Be6+ so black has to remove his bishop from under attack so his attack is for now tamed
as intended before I now occupy the open column with my rook

preventing Be6+ so if black plays h5 I have to capture the knight on d7 but them I saw a tactical blow that allowed me to win a pawn if I play Bxd7! black has two choices:
a) Qxd7 removing the guard from b6 and losing a pawn and a quality to Nxb6 with a double attack on queen and rook a8
b) Bxd7 an the queen is overcharged with the defence of b6 and d7
so Bxd7! was played and I expected the sequence Bxd7 Nxb6 Qxb6 Rxd7
and now the events turned I have the upper hand my rook is on the 7th rank and black has one pawn less also his bishops is a bad bishop considering the e5 and f4 pawns that block it
to challenge my rook's occupation of the 7th rank
zwischenzug with tempo to set a trap on black

here is the trap I left the pawn hanging to infiltrate black's 7th rank with my queen if Qxc5 then Qb3+ with tempo and then I have the sequence Qh8 (forced as Qf8 is mate after Qf7++) Qf7 (threatens mate in one) Rxd7 (not forced but a possible sequence) Qxe8+ Kg7 (forced) Qxd7+
and black resigned in face with the severe material loses he will have
Book through here.
The simpler I can make the game the better my chances. So any and all exchanges are welcome.
Trading off the other set of Bishops.
Supporting my lone advanced piece.
Opening a file to get rid of some of the heavy artillery.
The Queens are gone and now I threaten to swap off a pair of Rooks.
White is temporarily up a Pawn but it's  doubled and isolated. Plus I now threaten to win it back.
I do win it back and threaten to remove the last pair of Rooks as well. But White has undoubled his Pawns as compensation.

Now the ending is simple enough that I should be able to hold my own. And material is even. I offered a draw somewhere around here but White still thought he had wiinning chances against me and refused it.
I begin centralizing my King.
The Knights come off the board leaving a pure King and Pawn ending.
With the Kings in opposition it's now a question of who first runs out of Pawn moves.
More maneuvering...
I force his King to move first.
A Queening "race" will shortly begin.
And they're off!
If i foolishly play 39... PxP? I lose a tempo in the race.
It's a tie! The ending remains level.
Technically I'm now ahead one Pawn. But with an open board....
Draw agreed.

Diagrama # Sin duda alguna esta es la jugada que más me gusto de toda la partida. En apariencia resulta un tanto insulsa e innecesaria pero se basa en un conocidísimo concepto que ya teorizó el mismísmo Nimzowitch. En su obra "Mi Sistema" habló por primera vez de la sobreprotección de un punto. En concreto puso el ejemplo de la variante del avance de la defensa francesa y defendía la postura de que era muy útil sobreproteger el punto "d4" aunque ya estuviese suficientemente defendido para así poder liberar de su defensa a otras piezas que pudieran desarrolar funciones más efectivas. Volviendo a la posición que nos acontece esa fue precisamente mi idea. Así que tan sólo nos quedará ver si estas reflexiones "estratégico-filosóficas" se adaptan a las necesidades reales de la posición así que veamos...
Parece normal.
